transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thank you for calling. This is John. How can I help you?

Speaker 2: Yeah, John, I hope you can help me.

Speaker 1: My name is Bob Cohen, and I've tried to get, on more than one occasion,

Speaker 2: your product, the Viagra AGV.

Speaker 1: The first time I was denied when I gave my write-up,

Speaker 2: and then when I called you guys back,

Speaker 1: I said, if my cardiologist would write a letter, would we be approved?

Speaker 2: And he said, sure, if the cardiologist writes a letter, we don't need a script.

Speaker 1: We just need a letter from the cardiologist.

Speaker 2: So my cardiologist sent a letter that described that I can take 50 milligrams,

Speaker 1: that he recommends the 50 milligrams versus the 100 milligrams.

Speaker 2: You guys first came back to me with, okay, you're approved.

Speaker 1: We'll send it out.

Speaker 2: And then when the doctor got a hold of it, he saw the letter,

Speaker 1: and the letter included all of the drugs that I'm taking for years and years and years.

Speaker 2: And one of the drugs he put on the sheet was nitroglycerin, which I do not take.

Speaker 1: Okay? I have not taken it.

Speaker 2: It's in the sink.

Speaker 1: So the doctor, I called the doctor because you guys denied me,

Speaker 2: and the reason you denied me again is because on the list it showed nitroglycerin.

Speaker 1: I immediately called the doctor, my cardiologist,

Speaker 2: and said I'm not taking nitroglycerin.

Speaker 1: That's a mistake.

Speaker 2: He said, Bob, you're right.

Speaker 1: I'm sorry.

Speaker 2: It was a mistake by my people that typed it.

Speaker 1: I'll redo the letter without nitroglycerin.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: I now have the letter in hand, and I can send it back to you,

Speaker 1: and with a cover letter that it was a mistake on the part of my doctor.

Speaker 2: Yeah.

Speaker 1: If you can do that, and I actually talked to you the very first time.

Speaker 2: I was the one who spoke to you and told you about it.

Speaker 1: You can send in the letter.

Speaker 2: So, yes, send that in, and we'll resubmit it again saying that there's no nitroglycerin

Speaker 1: because I just took a look at your account, sir, and it's exactly what you said.

Speaker 2: The doctor did initially say it was okay, and then they saw the nitroglycerin and denied it.

Speaker 1: So we should be fine.

Speaker 2: Yeah.

Speaker 1: Yeah.

Speaker 2: So you think I'll be okay the third time?

Speaker 1: I do think so with this addendum to it, with the cover letter and everything.

Speaker 2: I think we'll be okay.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: The doctor is not saying anything in the letter different other than the removal of nitroglycerin.

Speaker 1: That's exactly what the sticking point was anyway.

Speaker 2: So if the doctor is signing off saying I included this when he's no longer taking it or is not taking it, that'll be-

Speaker 1: No, but he's not saying that.

Speaker 2: He just took nitroglycerin out, left the rest of the letter the same.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: That's fine, sir.

Speaker 1: Again, I don't know how to say it any other way.

Speaker 2: The issue here was nitroglycerin.

Speaker 1: So if he's taking that out, it should be fine.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: Do me a favor because it's been a while.

Speaker 2: Can you give me your e-mail once again?

Speaker 1: Do you want me just to e-mail you and you just reply to it?

Speaker 2: Yes.

Speaker 1: That would be good.

Speaker 2: Sure.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: I'll do that and then-

Speaker 1: Do you have my e-mail?

Speaker 2: Do you have my e-mail?

Speaker 1: Yes.

Speaker 2: I actually have the e-mail you sent, the B-colon at Prestige Group, that e-mail.

Speaker 1: That's right.

Speaker 2: Yes.

Speaker 1: Send it back to me and then I'll send it to you.

Speaker 2: Okay?

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: Sounds good.

Speaker 1: Thank you.

Speaker 2: What's your name?

Speaker 1: My name's John.

Speaker 2: John, thanks for your help.

Speaker 1: Welcome, sir.
